<FIRST>r w PM-FCC-Minorities     04-01 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FCC-Minorities,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minority-Preference Rules Held Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is being forced to review its policy of favoring minorities in the sale of `` distressed'' radio and TV stations because a court says the program is unconstitutional. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s 1978 `` distress sale'' rules, which allow quick sales at reduced rates of defunct or disenfranchised stations to blacks, Hispanics and other minorities, violate the equal protection provisions of the Fifth Amendment to the Constitution, a federal appeals court said Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, in a 2-1 vote, overturned a purchase after a <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, broadcaster said he should have been able to try to buy a station being offered in a distress sale. The ruling is at odds with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which in December 1987 refused _ with then-President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> concurring _ to allow the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to consider changing the policy. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> had said it wanted to review the policy after the appeals court in 1986 rejected a sale based on the agency's `` comparative preference'' program of giving special treatment to women seeking FM station licenses But after <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> acted, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> voted 3-0 in February 1988 to reaffirm the distress sale and female preference policies. It was not clear Friday how the commission would react to the latest remand. <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said she strongly supported minority entry into broadcasting and that the court had struck down a program mandated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are now between the proverbial rock and a hard place,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> also said he supported ensuring minority participation in broadcasting, but also that `` race alone should not control the licensing of broadcast stations.'' The Media Access Center, which filed a friend-of-the-court brief in the case, said the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> policy had worked well and the court `` made a mistake.'' <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartzman </PERSON>, the center's executive director, said `` we expect that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> or the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> will reinstate the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s policy. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> in 1984 denied <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shurberg </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Shurberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> a chance to compete for the purchase of WHCT-TV in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> from the station's owner. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> also affirmed that a rival for the <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> station, <ORGANIZATION> Astroline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partnership </ORGANIZATION>, was a minority enterprise and not a sham, as <PERSON> Shurberg </PERSON> contended. The appeals court Friday said the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> policy did not meet previous <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> tests of minority set-aside programs, including one that preferences be given to minorities only after race-neutral efforts to increase minority ownership had failed. `` The distress sale policy is not narrowly tailored to remedy past discrimination ... and it provides no procedures for ensuring that the policy's beneficiaries have actually suffered from the effects of past discrimination,'' Judge <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Silberman </PERSON> said in the majority opinion. Chief Judge <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wald </PERSON> dissented, saying the distress sale policy legally worked to ensure diversity in programming and ownership and that it was `` narrowly tailored to address the critical entry barriers to minority participation in media ownership while imposing only minimal burdens on innocent third parties.'' <PERSON> Shurberg </PERSON>, speaking by phone from <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, said he was `` delighted'' with the court's ruling.
