<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESWICK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Panza </PERSON> does n't understand why local tax officials wo n't let him pay back taxes with a little piggy that has yet to go market. <PERSON> Panza </PERSON> said he'll try to pay the debt again Tuesday by offering his pig, Art, to the city. Earlier this week, <PERSON> Panza </PERSON> donned his overalls, placed Art in a pickup truck and parked it outside the office of District Magistrate <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabulsky </PERSON>. `` Them pigs are my net profit,'' he told the magistrate, insisting it's legal to pay with pork. A <LOCATION> Harmar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION> ordinance allows him to pay with his income, which happens to be pigs, he said. <PERSON> Sabulsky </PERSON> ordered <PERSON> Panza </PERSON> to release his personal records so tax collectors could calculate how much he owes the township and the area school district. `` I've been fighting this for 13 years,'' <PERSON> Panza </PERSON> said. `` First of all, they're being a pig about all these taxes. You've got to pay property tax, school tax, township tax, and then they want to tax your net profit. There's nothing left for you.'' <PERSON> Sabulsky </PERSON> would n't say whether he'll accept the pig as payment.
