<HEAD>Philosophers To Debate On The Existence Of Color</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Roses are red, violets are blue. ... Or are they? Philosophers from around the country will gather in <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON> next week to discuss whether color is only in the eye of the beholder. The eighth annual colloquium in philosophy April 6-7 at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> will include presentations by professors from <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> universities, as well as <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. `` What's at issue is whether we have color in the world in the same way that we have shape in the world,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Darwall </PERSON>, the philosophy department chairman at <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. When it comes to color, philosophers tend to fall into two camps. Some argue that colors have an objective existence independent of our perception of them, <PERSON> Darwall </PERSON> said. Others argue that color is an illusion; that an object's characteristics cause it to reflect light a certain way, making people believe they are seeing a certain color, he added The question of color is recognized as a primary element in the debate between philosophers supporting a realistic outlook and their counterparts advocating an anti-realist point of view, <PERSON> Darwall </PERSON> said. `` It's a litmus test for different philosophical points of view,'' <PERSON> Darwall </PERSON> said of the color clash. Not much is expected to be resolved at the conference, <PERSON> Darwall </PERSON> said. `` It's not the case in philosophy that we get discoveries that are recognized instantly by all credible philosophers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
