<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Rights,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty International Says Soviet Rights Abuses Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet authorities have released hundreds of dissidents from confinement, but at least 100 remain in prisons, labor camps and psychiatric hospitals, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> reported. The group released its latest Soviet human rights report on Friday, two days after the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s executive committee voted to readmit a Soviet organization. Many psychiatrists in that association were reported opposed to the decision, which must be approved by its general assembly later this year. However, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> officials declined comment on that vote. The human rights organization said it had asked to speak with Soviet officials about the cases during the three-day visit of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, which begins Wednesday. They said they had received no response. Amnesty also said in its report that <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> citizens still could be prosecuted for exercising free speech or religion. `` Although there has been much improvement and discussion of human rights in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, and the rhetoric of human rights will no doubt dominate next week's visit, the reality is that there are still serious human rights concerns there,'' said <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Staunton </PERSON>, director of the group's British section. She and the coordinator for <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> affairs, <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Venables </PERSON>, spoke to reporters about <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s most recent briefing paper on Soviet human rights, dated March 1989. It says <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> knows of at least 100 prisoners known or thought to be dissidents, including 25 in psychiatric hospitals, but that 300 have been freed since 1987. Although some prisoners have been transferred to better facilities since 1987, those still in labor camps and prisons `` are kept on monotonous, meager rations with only rudimentary medical care, and have to meet excessively high work targets, often involving heavy physical labor,'' the report said. <PERSON> Venables </PERSON> added: `` There has been no major improvement in the condition of prisoners. Cruelty and degrading treatment still continues.'' Psychiatric patients are given unnecessary drugs, a treatment `` meted out as a form of intimidation,'' he said. Most of the 100 prisoners are people who tried to emigrate without permission or conscientious objectors to mandatory military service, <PERSON> Amnesty </PERSON> said. It said others are held for violating laws that restrict freedom of expression, religion, assembly and association. It welcomed elements of the new Soviet criminal code that recognize international rights agreements, abolish internal exile and reduce the number of capital crimes from 18 to six. A delegation from Amnesty is currently in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for a nine-day visit that is scheduled to end Sunday.
</TEXT>
