<FIRST>r a PM-FusionReport     04-01 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Report,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Fusion Experiment Gives Hope, But Far From Proven, Scientist
Cautions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A scientist who reported that a simple apparatus may create fusion power at room temperature said his work gives hope for a new energy source, but warned that `` fusion fever'' enthusiasm is premature. `` I think we have a new approach to fusion,'' but it is too early to say whether it will prove useful for generating electricity, said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Provo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. The results still must withstand scientific scrutiny and be confirmed by other scientists, and until that happens, `` do n't sell your oil well,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. Even if the results hold up, it would take many years before the process could be put to practical use, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said Friday at a physics colloquium and a later press conference at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Fusion is the process that powers the sun and stars, where tremendous amounts of energy are released when the nucleus, or core, of one hydrogen atom fuses with the nucleus of another hydrogen atom. In contrast, today's nuclear power plants get energy from fission, which is the splitting of atoms. Scientists hope to harness fusion power, saying it provides an environmentally benign energy source with a virtually unlimited source of fuel: `` heavy'' hydrogen, which occurs naturally in water. Standard fusion experiments use extremely high temperatures to get the hydrogen atoms to fuse. But <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and scientists at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> announced recently that they had independently found a simple way to produce fusion reactions at room temperature. Essentially, they used electrical current to herd hydrogen atoms into metal electrodes, where the hydrogen atoms apparently fused. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> researchers said their apparatus produced four times as much energy as it consumed. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, in contrast, said the <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> device appeared to produce only about one ten-trillionth of the energy put into it. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said he had not read the other team's scientific paper and could not explain the difference. The <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> apparatus included a pair of electrodes immersed in `` heavy water,'' in which hydrogen atoms contain an extra particle called a neutron in the nucleus. This kind of hydrogen is called deuterium. When low voltage was applied to the electrodes, deuterium nuclei were drawn into one of the electrodes. There, they apparently crowded together closely enough to fuse, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. Researchers calculated that two fusions occurred every five seconds, which would yield an energy output of one ten-trillionth of a watt. One watt is about enough to run an electric toothbrush. The evidence for fusion was that the apparatus emitted neutrons, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. That happened when the nuclei were driven into electrodes made from either titanium or palladium, with titanium giving the better results, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` We do n't really have a good theory'' to explain the fusion, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. Perhaps deuterium nuclei are forced close enough to fuse while hopping from site to site within the crystal structure of the electrode, he said. He calls the fusion approach piezonuclear fusion, because `` piezo'' means `` to squeeze.'' A similar process may cause part of the heat at the Earth's core, he said In <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, one of two researchers who first announced the discovery, <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON>, said Friday he had found no chemical explanation for the process by which he achieved sustained, controlled nuclear fusion in a simple experiment. `` It can not be explained by any known chemical process,'' said <PERSON> Pons </PERSON>, a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION>. `` I can conceive of no other process other than a nuclear process'' to explain the results.
</TEXT>
