<HEAD>Police Battle Dockworkers, Students Outside Shipyard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of dockworkers and students armed with clubs, firebombs and rocks fought police for the second consecutive day today, protesting a police crackdown that ended a prolonged strike at the nation's largest shipyard. About 3,500 protesters took to the streets of <LOCATION> Ulsan </LOCATION>, about 150 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, in scattered protests, news reports said. Police fired tear gas and charged the protesters, who responded with rocks and firebombs in hit-and-run battles, according to the South Korean news agency <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION>. The report said nothing of arrests or injuries. Thousands of riot police guarded <LOCATION> Ulsan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> shipyard, where the strike was broken up, and established checkpoints around bus terminals and on roads leading to the shipyard to block sympathizers from joining the protesters, it said. In <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, about 1,000 students supporting <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> strikers battled riot police around <ORGANIZATION> Hanyang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> for an hour after burning effigies of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo and <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION>. The Ulsan shipyard is owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> group, one of the largest conglomerates in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. One of its subsidiaries manufactures cars for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto market. Masked students brandishing firebombs streamed out of the gates, yelling `` Down with <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>, who stifles workers' rights!'' About 2,000 riot police sealed off the campus and fired hundreds of tear gas shells. There were no immediate reports of arrests and injuries in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Operations of the Hyundai shipyard remained slow, although more than half of its 22,000-member work force showed up for work today. Riot police stormed the shipyard Thursday in a land, sea and air attack to end the strike, whose violence injured about 400 people since December. <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION>'s trouble began last Dec. 12, when militant workers broke away from a company-sanctioned union and organized a separate group, demanding pay hikes and better working conditions. The police intervention triggered violent protests in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and other cities by strike sympathizers who accused the government of suppressing free labor and protecting conglomerates at the cost of workers.
