<DATELINE>TAHLEQUAH, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cherokee Indians from across the country are observing the 150th anniversary of the Trail of Tears, the forced march from their Southeastern homeland that claimed an estimated 4,000 lives. `` In Cherokee memory it is only a short time ago,'' <PERSON> Wilma </PERSON> <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Cherokee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oklahoma </ORGANIZATION>, told about 300 people gathered Friday on the lawn of the old Cherokee national capitol in this northeast <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> city of 10,000. The observance ends today. The forced relocation of much of the tribe to <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> ended in late 1839. Of the estimated 4,000 Cherokees who died, many were buried in unmarked graves. `` And yet here we are. Here we are. Despite everything that has happened to us,'' Ms. <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON> said. Today, the 93,000-member <LOCATION> Cherokee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tribe </LOCATION> is the nation's second largest, behind the Navajos. Ms. <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON> and Chief <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> of the eastern band of Cherokees from <LOCATION> Cherokee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, planted an oak tree on the capitol grounds `` in memory of many people who were on the trail who did not make it to the new home,'' said Deputy Chief <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ketcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tahlequah </LOCATION>. Officials had made it clear the prayers and speeches were to be more a memorial service than a celebration, but some said their ancestors' travails 150 years ago were not being emphasized enough. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Moss </PERSON> of <PERSON> Stilwell </PERSON>, vice chairman of Native Americans for a Clean Environment, asked that April 1 be recognized as an international day of sorrow in memory of those who died on the Trail of Tears. `` The forced relocation of Cherokee and other indigenous people, known as the Trail of Tears, was an act of genocide,'' <PERSON> Moss </PERSON> said. `` While it is a very, very sad time in our history, I still believe we can draw strength from our ancestors,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON>. `` I've been able to draw strength from that terrible time in our history.'' She emphasized that when they were relocated the Cherokees were a civilized, self-governing tribe. The tribe survived the Trail of Tears to reform its government, establish schools, and erect civic buildings in northeast <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. However, in 1906 the tribe's land was taken away; members were given individual allotments. The Cherokees had no constitutional tribal government until 1971, when the capitol was re-established in <LOCATION> Tahlequah </LOCATION>.
