<HEAD>Najib: Firm Talk and a Big, Big Stick</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By Earleen Fisher</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>Kabul, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It might be easy for those on the outside to dismiss President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> as a hulking, former secret police chief presiding over a repressive government destined for defeat. But this same man has proved himself to be an eloquent orator, a shrewd combatant during political infighting, and a politician deft at appealing to feelings of nationalism. The test now at hand is the battle for <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, where U.S.-supported Moslem guerrillas have besieged <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s forces nearly four weeks. Neither side has been able to claim victory. Thousands of people have surely died, although neither side has sufficient credibility for its casualty reports to be believed. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> has fired his biggest guns, literally and figuratively. The Soviet-supplied Scud-B missiles launched toward <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> several times a day are monster-size weapons, but their impact may be as much psychological as physical. The government makes no effort to conceal its Scuds, trundling the 36-foot-long missiles through the center of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> on open truck beds in broad daylight. The roar with which they are fired is unmistakable. Their message _ and that of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> MiGs and Sukhois _ is clear: <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s weapons outclass any rockets, mortars or shells the guerrillas can pack across the border from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Although the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> withdrew the last of its combat troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on Feb. 15, it continues to supply the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government with Scuds, smaller weapons and food and says it will do so as long as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> aids the guerrillas. The guerrillas are caught in a dilemma. They are most effective in hit-and-run attacks, not bogged down in confrontation with a regular army that outnumbers and outguns them. Conversely, regular armies rarely vanquish guerrilla forces militarily, as the Israelis learned against the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and the Indians against Tamil guerrillas in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. The most effective solution is a political one, which is impossible to achieve unless both sides agree to negotiate. But guerrilla leaders refuse to talk to <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and say they will not give up the fight until his Soviet-style party is removed. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> is giving the political side his best shot. `` Fratricide brings nothing but misery and agony,'' the president said last week in a radio appeal aimed at the guerrillas' local commanders inside <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> Referring to them as `` dear compatriots'' and `` my brothers'' and to their Pakistan-based political leaders as `` the enemy'' and `` the extremists,'' <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> offered a cease-fire and local autonomy to commanders who would stop fighting. From guerrilla headquarters in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> came a rejection of <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s offer. But the government claims it has opened negotiations with some local commanders it refused to identify. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> rarely misses an opportunity to accuse <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of `` vicious warmongering,'' of imposing a foreign-inspired war on Afghans. It is a calculated ploy aimed at the fiercely independent and tribalistic Afghans' centuries-old antipathy to outsiders. There also seems to be a growing feeling in war-weary <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, although unquestionably an authoritarian leader, is not as bad as his predecessors in the ruling <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION>. The Afghan monarchy ended in 1973 when King <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> was overthrown by a cousin, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Daoud </PERSON>. Five years later, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> overthrew and assassinated <PERSON> Daoud </PERSON>, bringing <PERSON> Noor </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Taraki </PERSON> to power. <PERSON> Taraki </PERSON> himself was killed in 1979 as party rival <PERSON> Hafizullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> took over. With the <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> regime teetering under guerrilla attacks and party feuds, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> sent troops to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> later that year and <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> was assassinated. <PERSON> Amin </PERSON>'s successor, <PERSON> Babrak </PERSON> <PERSON> Karmal </PERSON>, in turn was shunted aside by <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the London-based human rights monitoring group, estimated that 35,000 Afghans have been imprisoned or disappeared _ the majority of them in the pre-Najib early 1980s. Under <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, there are still political arrests but the number of detentions has dropped sharly, according to several foreign observers who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` <PERSON> Taraki </PERSON>, <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Babrak </PERSON> were crazy men. Maybe <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> is not so bad,'' said one businessman. Others have expressed similar views. The party traditionally is divided between the <LOCATION> Parcham </LOCATION> faction headed by <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and the Khalq faction of the late <PERSON> Taraki </PERSON> and <PERSON> Amin </PERSON>. In October, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> purged Parchami dissidents and a month later dispatched the top <PERSON> Khalqi </PERSON> leader, Gen. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Gulabzoi </PERSON>, to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> as ambassador _ a time-tested Afghan way of getting potential troublemakers out of the country.
</TEXT>
