<HEAD>Gorbachev Picks Neutral Ireland for First Western Appearance This
Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev-Cuba, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For his first appearance in the West since the Armenian earthquake cut short his <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visit in December, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has chosen a small nation that in some ways straddles <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s political, social and military divides. The Soviet president's stopover Sunday at <LOCATION> Shannon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> en route to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and then <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is the first visit by a Soviet leader to this 95-percent Roman Catholic country. As the most Catholic nation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> is instinctively anti-communist, and 85 percent of the population votes for conservative parties. But it also cherishes the neutrality that kept it out of World War II and makes it the only member of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> to stay out of the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s drive to harmonize its members' policies leads some Irish to worry their neutrality is being compromised, and a visit by the leader of the communist world could help restore the balance. For a country of 3.5 million people still undergoing the transition from a rural to industrial society, even a brief visit from a Soviet leader is a big prestige boost. Irish newspapers Saturday devoted special sections to the visit, which the Irish Times described as confirmation of Prime Minister <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Haughey </PERSON>'s `` role as an international statesman.'' The Irish Independent said the visit was both `` significant and symbolic.'' <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Frost </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZAT