<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge, citing a lack of evidence, has freed two former military officials and an industrialist jailed three years ago in a highly publicized probe into right-wing kidnappings. Judge <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Larios </PERSON> on Friday ordered the release of former Lt. <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Sibrian </PERSON>, former Maj. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> and industrialist <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Llovera </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballete </PERSON>. <PERSON> Larios </PERSON> also canceled arrest warrants for five other people, including a former army colonel. The judge declared null the acts of a military judge who in 1986 started the proceedings. The case was transferred to civilian court in 1988 after it was ruled the crimes were not politically motivated. <PERSON> Larrios </PERSON> said statements from witnesses on the kidnappings were not reliable and that there was insufficient evidence to hold the men. The government alleged that <PERSON> Llovera </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballete </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Sibrian </PERSON> posed as leftist guerrillas to capture five businessmen in exchange for about $ 5 million between 1980 and 1985. The two were reported to be close friends of cashiered army Maj. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON>, founder of the ultra-conservative <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>. The party's candidate, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, won the March 16 presidential election. <PERSON> D'Aubuisson </PERSON> and his associates have been repeatedly linked to right-wing death squads that ran rampant in the country in the early 1980s. <PERSON> D'Aubuisson </PERSON> has denied the charges. When police agents captured <PERSON> Llovera </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballete </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Sibrian </PERSON> in March 1986, it was widely viewed as the start of a case that would pit the administration of <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> against the conservative sectors of the military. Also implicated in the case were <LOCATION> Oporto </LOCATION> Tereson Roman, <PERSON> Moises </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Arriola </PERSON> and detective <PERSON> Edgardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Linates </PERSON>, who all died under suspicious circumstances in the following months. One was found hanged in his jail cell, another was shot when he reportedly tried to escape police custody, and the other was gunned down just outside <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Authorities said the three could have provided important information in the case. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Sibrian </PERSON> also was implicated in the 1981 murders of two <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> land advisers _ <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearlman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION>, Md. _ and a Salvadoran agrarian reform official. The charges against <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Sibrian </PERSON>, who was later dismissed from the army, were dropped because of lack of evidence. <PERSON> Pearlman </PERSON> and Hammer were advising the government on a land reform program that took thousands of acres from wealthy families and distributed them to peasants. Five years later, two former army corporals were convicted in the case. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government later maintained that the `` intellectual authors'' of the crime had not been brought to justice.
