<HEAD>Afghan Guerrillas Step Up Attack On Jalalabad</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Najib, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Moslem guerrillas, bolstered by newly arrived reinforcements, intensified their rocket and artillery attacks on the government-held city of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Saturday. Guerrilla bombardments on Thursday and Friday killed 69 civilians and wounded 123, the government said. It was one of the highest civilian death tolls reported since the U.S.-backed guerrillas launched their offensive March 6 in an effort to oust government troops from the city 75 miles east of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. The siege began less than three weeks after the last Soviet troops withdrew from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> after nine years of support for successive regimes in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Amani </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, reported eight deaths and 27 injuries among government troops and said 109 opposition fighters were killed and 70 wounded. Most of the figures could not be verified, but members of the <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> religious minority who arrived in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> on Saturday said 22 people were killed Thursday in a Sikh Gurdwara, or temple, in <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>. They said hundreds of people had taken refuge in the Gurdwara as rocket and shell fire intensified, and they said few people were venturing outside. <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said 12,000 to 14,000 opposition fighters, including what he said were `` Pakistani militiamen in Afghan costume,'' were attacking <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> early in the week and an additional 3,500 men had joined them by Saturday. He said the new fighters came from <LOCATION> Paktia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Paktika </LOCATION> provinces, which are southwest of <LOCATION> Nangarhar </LOCATION> province where <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> is located. He did not say how many government soldiers were defending the city. The government spokesman said the opposition on Thursday fired 16,000 shells and rockets at <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> and that 2,500 of them fell in residential areas and destroyed 13 houses. On Friday, he said, 900 more rockets and shells hit residential aras, destroying 43 houses. He did not give a total number of rounds fired on all targets Friday. <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> also read a Foreign Ministry statement accusing the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> foreign </ORGANIZATION> secretary, Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, of trying to reimpose British colonialism on <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> through its support for the Moslem insurgency. <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> met Moslem guerrilla leaders in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> last week. In <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> on Friday, he said only a broad-based Afghan government will bring peace. He said he found the guerrilla leaders were willing `` to work for a government that will command a wide acceptance inside the country.'' But he said such a government must not be imposed on the Afghan people. On Feb. 23, the guerrillas met in <LOCATION> Rawalpindi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, and elected a provisional government they hope will replace President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and his Soviet-style <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Thousands of people have fled <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> since the fighting started, and the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government says it does not know how many remain in the city. <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> had a population of 200,000 a decade ago, but it generally was thought to have shrunk to less than half that number before the guerrilla offensive started. The city is key for the insurgents, for it would give them a base on Afghan soil to set up their provisional government.
