<HEAD>Man Confesses To Wife's Death 12 Years Ago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTESANO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man has confessed to killing his wife 12 years ago in what authorities at the time thought was a traffic accident. A confession by <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Potter </PERSON>, 55, of <PERSON> Humptulips </PERSON> was contained in sworn statements unsealed Friday in <ORGANIZATION> Grays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harbor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. According to the documents, <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> said he was driven by guilt to approach county authorities two weeks ago and admit that he killed his wife in a fight. `` I had no right to take her life,'' he said. `` She was making my life so miserable that I had to get rid of her,'' <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> told sheriff's deputies in his confession. `` I decided I was going to enjoy my life a little bit and just lay her in the ground where she belonged.'' <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> was arrested Friday for investigation of murder. He was being held in the county jail pending a decision by county Prosecutor <PERSON> Steward </PERSON> <PERSON> Menefree </PERSON> on whether to file charges. Earlier this week, the county sheriff's office exhumed the body of <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Potter </PERSON>, who was 40 when she died in 1976. An autopsy was conducted by the <LOCATION> King </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> medical examiner, and results have been sent to <LOCATION> Grays </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> authorities. In statements to police, <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> described himself as driven by a rage because `` my wife would do nothing for me, but she expected everything from me.'' He said he has now realized his anger `` was n't a sane way of thinking.'' <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> said that on the evening of Nov. 28, 1976, he asked his wife to accompany him to a tavern in <LOCATION> Humptulips </LOCATION>, 80 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, for a drink. They went, and each had a drink, but `` she would n't talk to me,'' he said. The couple returned home, but <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> said his wife refused to come inside, `` so I started after her.'' `` I grabbed her by the coat front and hit her,'' he said. `` As far as I know, it broke her jaw and knocked her unconscious. She fell, and I was still in such a rage that I got down alongside of her. I guess I straddled her and started strangling her.'' As his wife's breathing became fainter, <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> said he `` got to feeling sorry for her,'' and tried to revive her with mouth-to-mouth resuscitation. He decided to take her to a hospital, but changed his mind on the way. `` I thought if I took her to the hospital she could take me to a court of law to have me put away for being violent,'' he said. Instead, he drove down an isolated road, where he decided to `` wreck the car to either kill us both or to see if one of us was worth saving.'' He floored the accelerator and crashed the car into a bank of the twisting road. When <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> came to, he was slumped over the wheel. He noticed a cut on his forehead, he told deputies. His wife had been thrown 10 feet from the car. <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> said he approached where she lay and heard `` a rasping breath and she quit breathing.'' Had she not died at the scene, <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> later told police, he would have `` taken a tire iron and beat her to death.'' A court affidavit said investigating officers at the time accepted <PERSON> Potter </PERSON>'s explanation of the accident, and no autopsy was conducted, even though his wife had indicated to a minister she feared for her life. Menefree, the county prosecutor, said the autopsy confirmed <PERSON> Potter </PERSON>'s description of the fight. He declined to give specifics, but said autopsy results `` fit into the whole puzzle we're piercing together.''
