<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Elections,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraqi Elect New National Assembly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iraqis crowded polling stations nationwide Saturday to elect a new 250-member National Assembly in what was seen as the first step toward democracy after 20 years of one-party rule. Twelve hours of voting ended at 8 p.m. and election committee officials began counting votes in more than 900 polling stations around the country. Officials said the turnout was relatively high, but exact figures were not immediately available. They said the first returns would be announced Sunday with final results not expected until Monday. About 2 million of the estimated 8 million voters live in the capital, <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, which had 59 polling stations. The government-controlled media called the election, the first since the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, `` a celebration of democracy'' and called on Iraqis to cast ballots `` as a national duty.'' Columnist <PERSON> Daoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Farhan </PERSON> wrote in the <LOCATION> Al-Qaddissiya </LOCATION> newspaper that voters should elect people who would work for `` a permanent constitution, general freedoms, a multiparty system, reasonable prices, housing for all, improved social services, comprehensive health insurance, defense of human rights and battling embezzlers and thieves.'' The assembly is expected to endorse a new constitution and a new law establishing a multiparty system after 20 years of rule by the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baath </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Polling day was declared a national holiday to ensure a big voter turnout, and stores and offices were closed. Nearly 700 independent candidates, more than in two previous assembly elections, ran for the part-time legislature. In addition, there were 260 candidates from the ruling party, although authorities have stressed they are not members of an official ticket. Forty-two candidates were dropped at the last minute when it was discovered in snap tests they could not read or write, the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> announced Friday night. The assembly, elected to a four-year term, shares legislative power with the Council, which must ratify draft laws and also has veto power. Diplomats and political analysts say the election outcome may influence future policy-making by enabling independents to play a bigger role in decision making. But no timetable has been set for the political reforms, and they are not expected to reduce President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s personal power. A referendum will be held on the new constitution, which will replace an interim charter approved in 1969, one year after the Baath party seized power in a bloodless coup. The elections originally were set for last Aug. 30 but were postponed until March 3 after the U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in the gulf war took effect The second delay was to allow more independents to run, the government said. The candidates, including 62 women and many gulf war veterans, staged low-key campaigns, confined under government rules to making brief speeches to organized gatherings and answering a few questions. Their campaigns were funded by the government and candidates were banned from using any of their own financial resources.
</TEXT>
