<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices tripled Saturday for rice, fuel, cooking gas and airline tickets after <LOCATION> Guyana </LOCATION> devalued its currency by 230 percent and doubled interest rates to 35 percent. The government increased wages only 20 percent in the move, which was made to meet International Monetary Fund conditions for aid. Finance Minister <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenidge </PERSON> announced the move during a budget hearing late Friday to cries of `` shame, shame and hardship'' from opposition lawmakers. `` This is a budget of violence,'' said <PERSON> Cheddi </PERSON> <PERSON> Jagan </PERSON>, leader of the Marxist opposition <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The Mirror, an opposition newspaper, called the devaluation `` murderous.'' Average daily wages in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nation are $ 2.30, while a loaf of bread costs $ 5. The <LOCATION> Guyana </LOCATION> dollar, previously fixed at 10 to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, is now worth 33.3 to the dollar. However, by Saturday the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar was fetching 62 <LOCATION> Guyana </LOCATION> dollars on the black market. Though the tough austerity measures were taken to satisfy <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> conditions for a $ 1.9 billion aid package, <PERSON> Greenidge </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> has refused to conclude the deal until <LOCATION> Guyana </LOCATION> raises an additional $ 50 million to clear back payments to the fund. <PERSON> Greenidge </PERSON> said the government expects to raise the money in two weeks. <LOCATION> Guyana </LOCATION>, which has had no economic growth in 10 years, is attempting to secure the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> package to revamp its stagnant economy. This former British colony's main foreign-exchange earning exports _ bauxite, sugar and rice _ recorded drops in production of up to 30 percent in 1988. For several months the nation of 750,000 has been plagued by power rationing and outages, food and fuel shortages and spiraling inflation, causing sporadic strikes and food riots. Since the death of <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> President </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forbes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> in 1985, President <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyte </PERSON> has moved toward a free-market system, divesting state enterprises and encouraging foreign capital investments.
