 <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Korn </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> researcher who helped create touch-tone telephones and the direct-dial long-distance system, has died at the age of 83. <PERSON> Korn </PERSON>, who retired from <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labs </ORGANIZATION> in 1970 after 50 years with the company, died at home Friday of kidney failure, said his daughter, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Trimmer </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudyk </PERSON>. <PERSON> Korn </PERSON> was director of telephone laboratories at the former <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> plant here now owned by <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T. He was credited with developing a nationwide direct-dial military telephone network during World War II, and with the development of touch-tone dialing. He also co-invented the switching system used by telephone companies until the mid-1970s, when electronic switching was introduced, according to <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Heckendorn </PERSON>, retired engineering manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> plant. <PERSON> Korn </PERSON> held about 15 telephone-related patents, said his grandson, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Trimmer </PERSON>, and was named a fellow of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>, the highest honor bestowed by the professional organization. He is survived by his wife, a daughter, two grandchildren and a great-grandchild, family members said.
