<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government study recommends a new penalty structure for doctors who provide poor quality care to <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> patients. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said the current system of limiting penalties to the amount of the cost to Medicaid sometimes results in penalties that are disproportionately low compared with the nature of the offense. For example, in one case the report said a doctor endangered a cardiac patient by releasing her from the hospital although she showed symptoms of a second heart attack. Because there was no additional cost to the Medicare program stemming from the doctor's negligence, no financial penalty could be imposed, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, recommended that the cost-based limit be replaced by a fixed upper limit on the size of monetary penalties. It did not recommend where the limit should be set. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said that in July 1987, the inspector general of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> advised peer review organizations not to recommend financial penalties unless the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> provider had displayed a pattern of poor care and a significant amount of Medicare payment to the doctor was involved. The inspector general has since decided to drop that criteria, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said, but as of February there had been no formal notification to halt the July 1987 criteria.
