<HEAD>Ariane Sends Satellite Into Orbit After One-Day Delay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOUROU, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s Ariane-2 rocket, after a 24-hour delay, lifted a communications satellite for <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> into Earth orbit Saturday night. The rocket was launched from the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> center at <LOCATION> Kourou </LOCATION> on the northern coast of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Arianespace </ORGANIZATION> officials announced 20 minutes after the launch that the mission was completed successfully, with the TELE-X satellite placed in orbit. The launch had been scheduled for Friday night but was postponed by a last-minute malfunction of the ground computer system. The satellite, a program of the three Nordic governments, is to provide direct television broadcasts to home satellite dishes and business communications between ground terminals. Swedish <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is overseeing the program. The satellite, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Nordic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is to serve up to 5,000 business users. Officials said the television signals will be powerful enough to be received by an antenna just 12 inches in diameter. Programming has not yet been lined up for the broadcasts. <ORGANIZATION> Arianespace </ORGANIZATION> is in charge of production, marketing and launches of the Ariane rockets developed by the 13-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> are among the member states while <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> is an associate member state. <ORGANIZATION> Arianespace </ORGANIZATION> carried out seven missions last year as well as successful launches on Jan. 26 and March 6 this year. There are 33 satellites on the <ORGANIZATION> Arianespace </ORGANIZATION> order book for future launches. The European consortium has captured about half of the world market for commercial satellite launches.
