July by British broadcaster <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> went to Australian businessman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Saffron </PERSON> in December. Italian producers <PERSON> Giancarlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Parretti </PERSON> and <PERSON> Florio </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiorini </PERSON> also have been picking up some of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, including the small studios <ORGANIZATION> Cannon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>. The UA-MGM deal, and the foreign invasion in general, have sparked the concern of at least one American network official, who questioned the fairness of federal regulations that forbid the networks from making the same kind of deals open to overseas firms. Rules drafted in the early 1970s, when the networks were the only television game in town and cable and pay-for-view were still about a decade away, prohibit the networks from going into the production business. `` Our view is that it is increasingly ironic and shortsighted to have policies on the books which allow foreign interests to dominate entertainment production while <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most logical competitors, the networks, continue to be shut out,'' said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON>, director of corporate communications for <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>.
