<HEAD>Vietnam's Communist Party Will Tolerate No Challenge To Its Authority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership has reaffirmed a need for reform but declared it will not tolerate any challenges to its authority or basic principles. Comprehensive reform requires efforts to `` broaden socialist democracy,'' but the party must tread carefully, party chief <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> told a March 20-29 conference of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Radio <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, in a report Saturday on the plenum, quoted <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> as saying: `` All attempts aimed at weakening or nullifying the party's leadership and creating political counterweights to the party in society must definitely be checked. `` We do not allow those who take advantage of democracy and openness to attack the party and its leadership,'' he said. `` It is necessary to clearly distinguish constructive criticism from mud-slinging and instigating attempts aimed at lowering the prestige of the party and state.'' The broadcast, monitored in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, reported <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> said the leadership advocates enhancing the roles of state-supervised mass organizations and of elected organs like the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. `` We advocate broadening democracy and reaching a consensus through debate, but we do not tolerate pluralism,'' he declared. <PERSON> Linh </PERSON>'s speech closed the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s sixth plenum, held to review reforms endorsed at the national party congress in 1986. <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> became party chief at the congress and three leaders identified with old policies retired. But Western analysts said party conservatives remain concerned that reforms may erode the dominant position of the party that achieved power after decades of fighting the French, Japanese and Americans and South Vietnamese anti-communists. Radio <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> reported <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that the party must avoid prejudice against private enterprises but also must not favor them `` without realizing their limits and spontaneity, which leads to lack of close management control.'' Without giving details, the broadcast reported <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> said the state will promulgate laws stipulating which industries can not be run by private individuals. <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s development requires increased commercial ties with non-socialist nations but that while ties were being expanded the party must watch out for `` negative influences.'' `` Once our door is open, not only will the pure and healthy air come in but dust, flies, and mosquitos also will follow,'' he said. A <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> communique, also carried by <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanoi </ORGANIZATION>, said reforms were designed not to change the goal of socialism but to achieve it more quickly. It said the reform of the political system `` is meant to strengthen the party's role of leadership and the state's managerial efficacy and the people's right to mastery. The communique blamed the uneven pace of reform on the `` many shortcomings'' of the party leadership and the state, with authorities slow to implement party resolutions and to make needed changes in the party and state structures. In his comments on the economy, <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> blamed inflation on the low output of state-run enterprises and the government's policy of subsidizing key areas of the economy. He said results of the reforms began to become visible in the third quarter of 1988 with more consumer goods and foodstuffs available, less strain in the grain supply and a slowing of the rate of price increases.
