<HEAD>Just When You Thought the Airline Business Was Settling Down...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is mostly mothballed, and <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is flying. But both are attracting bids from billionaire business celebrities ranging from hoteliers to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> investors. People who saw `` Wall Street'' may have thought they were watching real-life variants of the back-room maneuvering for the movie's fictional <ORGANIZATION> Bluestar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> if they followed accounts of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> this past week. The cast of contenders included baseball commissioner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>, Hyatt hotel chain owner <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON>, property-casino centurion <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> and energy-entertainment investor <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. Others said to be involved, either as buyers or their lenders, included takeover strategist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, who also is chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, reclusive <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> financier <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON>, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Batchelder </PERSON>, the former adviser to the dean of the corporate stalkers, oilman <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>. Miami-based Eastern remained comatose, its fate unclear, planes mostly grounded and assets increasingly mired in bankruptcy court proceedings, with little sign from parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> that a sale was close. A group led by <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> had offered $ 464 million offer for the airline, which prior to the March 4 strike flew 100,000 passengers daily to 118 cities with 250 jetliners. Since then it has barely managed a skeleton schedule. <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON> reportedly offered a higher price, value unknown. But <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>'s offer told a story in itself about the perceived worth of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, one of the nation's most unprofitable airlines. The <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> deal was $ 200 million below the price <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> paid three years ago, and barely $ 100 million over what <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> had offered for Eastern's Northeast shuttle, which flies to only three cities with about 20 planes. At Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, management was facing a $ 2.7 billion, $ 90-a-share takeover offer from <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, a second offer of undisclosed value from a group the airline would n't identify, and rumors that at least one other investor group was preparing to make a bid Not coincidentally, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> erected an anti-takeover `` poison pill'' shield to thwart unfriendly acquirers by making it prohibitively expensive for them to sell any of the airline's assets. The defense was designed to foil what many analysts have called the airline's biggest weakness: lucrative operations in the economically booming <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> region and a lagging domestic business. As the 1980s takeover era has shown, that kind of unwieldy, inefficient performance invites unsolicited offers from investors who see profit in selling a company in pieces. A takeover of Northwest therefore raised the prospect of the biggest airline bustup since deregulation, only three years after <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> acquired hometown rival <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> for $ 884 million. In other business and economic developments this past week: _ After months of rumor, a federal grand jury indicted <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> junk-bond pioneer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and two others in the biggest fraud and racketeering case in Wall Street history The defendants asserted innocence in a case that reflected the radical use of racketeering laws to prosecute white-collar suspects. It also created a forum for a courtroom fight between <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and his main accuser, imprisoned speculator <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>. _ More evidence emerged of a slowing economy The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the index of leading indicators fell 0.3 percent in February, largely because of a drop in factory orders and construction. The department also said home sales tumbled 9.4 percent in February. _ A stunning failure and a surprise merger proposal roiled the banking industry, reflecting the economy's disjointed regional growth Federal regulators seized most of Texas-based MCorp.'s 25 banks after it disclosed plans to seek Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> offered to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Souther </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in a stock-swap that would create the country's sixth-largest banking company. _ A monster Alaskan 