<HEAD>A Positive, But Wary First Quarter For Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market overcame a welter of worries to post some respectable gains in the first quarter of 1989. But misgivings about the financial and economic outlook are still very much in evidence as Wall Streeters look ahead to the remaining nine months of tho 10 percent range. If that kind of pace could be sustained over a year or two, it would qualify as a robust bull market. Yet little rejoicing has been heard in the investment community, which still evidently has n't quite gotten over the shock of the crash that occurred a year and a half ago. `` Since the great crash there has been no consistent theme or trend,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicoski </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jaffray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Hopwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. He describes the current mood of investors as one of `` pessimistic hope. `` The pessimism calls for a slowing economy and rising unemployment, whereas the hope is embedded in the belief this will cool inflation, diminish our trade imbalance and lower interest rates. `` The unlikelihood of all the preceding happening without a meaningful recession and sharply lower corporate profits has not gone unnoticed, however.'' Increased recession worries were evident from the behavior of diversified manufacturing, auto and machinery stocks, all of which ranked among the 10 worst performing industry groups for the quarter. In a compilation through March 29, <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said the manufacturing group was down 3.8 percent; the auto stocks dropped 2.6 percent, and the machinery group lost 1.5 percent. Over the same period, <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P's 500-stock composite index rose 5.3 percent, not counting dividends. Earnings worries, meanwhile, weighed heavily on technology stocks. The computer systems, electronic instrument, communications equipment and semiconductor groups all finished in the minus column. Some of the big winners _ such as the airlines, up 17.8 percent, and hospital management, up 20.2 percent _ got a lift from the continuing boom in takeover and buyout bids. For its part, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, with a 50.58 rise to 2,293.62 in the past week, closed out the quarter sporting a gain of 125.05 points, or 5.77 percent. Other readings for the week showed the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite index up 2.99 at 165.63; the <ORGANIZATION> NASDAQ </ORGANIZATION> composite index for the over-the-counter market up 5.79 at 406.73, and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> market value index up 3.44 at 328.31. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> averaged 146.91 million shares a day, against 148.40 million the week before. The crux of the market's problems right now, many analysts agree, is persistently high interest rates. `` The current environment, in any historical perspective, is unattractive for equities,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerschner </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` First, the relative safety of a guaranteed 10 percent one-year return stacks up well against the returns the equity market MIGHT deliver, even in the most benign environment. `` Second, the impact that these higher interest rates have in both depressing the corporate revenue line and increasing the corporate expense line suggests that the profit environment over the next few quarters might be far from benign. `` High interest rates have historically been a harbinger of a risky stock market, because they have been lead indicators of earnings disappointments.'' End Adv Weekend Editions for April 1-2
