<SECOND>BC-Milken-Con, Adv 03,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, April 3 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shed No Tears for Securities Violators</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Milken-Pro</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The indictment of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> last week marked a watershed in the federal crackdown on securities fraud, while inciting a heated debate over the use of the Racketeer Influenced and <ORGANIZATION> Corrupt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> law to catch alleged Wall Street wrongdoers Under the law, originally designed to combat organized crime, the government can seize assets of defendants before trial, creating intense pressure on them to strike a plea bargain. Below, and in an accompanying story, two prominent observers argue the pros and cons of the <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> case. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> is a legal scholar who consults extensively on RICO matters; <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Ingersoll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is a personal friend of <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Shed no tears for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> or his firm, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which has agreed to plead guilty to fraud rather than face racketeering charges under the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law. These prosecutions have provoked misplaced criticism of the RICO law. RICO critics argue that <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> was unfairly induced to capitulate. Supposedly, any other decision would have meant instant ruin, since RICO allows assets to be frozen pretrial and forfeited after conviction. No doubt <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> felt pressured, but stress is inherent in the plea negotiation process. Thus, street criminals often plead guilty to avoid habitual offender charges. A more important issue is whether <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> is guilty. The answer must be yes, for no judge may accept a baseless guilty plea. As the defense of `` good faith'' was readily available, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s megabuck legal team would not have advised a groundless plea. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> now has the same defense _ and others as well _ under <ORGANIZATION> RICO </ORGANIZATION>. Nor was <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> abused by a pretrial asset freeze. This procedure, incidentally, is not unique to RICO. Other laws provide similar remedies comparable to bail bonds used to secure personal appearances at trial. No evidence suggests forfeiture was maliciously threatened. Moreover, prosecutors may not impose forfeiture unilaterally. RICO requires proof of probable success at trial and the risk of asset dissipation. Moreover, the court must consider various equitable factors. And not all assets may be frozen, only those needed to ensure funds for payoff upon conviction. The government is also justified in seeking forfeiture. Forfeiture takes the profit out of crime, a penalty that works well against corporations which can not be jailed. In <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s case, the alleged profits would make successful drug dealers envious. Surely the narcotics crisis is not to be solved by encouraging drug dealers to turn to securities fraud. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reserved RICO for criminals who engage in a PATTERN of racketeering _ a requirement courts take seriously. Violators, therefore, merit special sanctions. White collar defendants claim to be unfairly stigmatized by the term racketeer. Perhaps `` swindler'' is more apt, but <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> properly considered white collar crimes to be racketeering. The legislative record is replete with references to corrupt businesses, including brokerage firms. Critics want to limit RICO to the Mafia. But white collar crime exacts equally serious social costs, and, constitutionally, we ought not tolerate efforts to confine racketeering laws to any ethnic group. Thus, though the case against <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> remains to be proven, if guilt is established, the RICO penalty would fit the crime.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Professor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> is </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vice-Chairman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Section </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> RICO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and consults extensively on RICO matters.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, April 3</NOTE>
